 (b) We can get rid of the square root with a trig substitution.
Substituting x=2\sin y, \dee{x}=2\cos y\ \dee{y},


\int\sqrt{4-x^2}\ \dee{x}
&=\int \sqrt{4-4\sin^2 y}\ 2\cos y\ \dee{y}
