&=3x^3 \arcsin x + 3\sqrt{1-x^2} - \sqrt{1-x^2}^3+C





Option 2: If we let x=\sin\theta, then \sqrt{1-x^2}=\sqrt{\cos^2\theta}=\cos\theta. So let's use the substitution x=\sin\theta, \dee{x}=\cos\theta \dee{\theta}.


\int (3x)^2\arcsin x \dee{x}&=
3x^3\arcsin x -\int \frac{3x^3}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dee{x}

